Node.Notes: Sense is that a curse does not come to rest on a person who does not deserve it.
Probably two figures comparing sending messages by the hand of a fool to doing yourself serious harm and suffering violence.
Verb "hang limp" (in sense of be useless) carried over from first half of verse.
Unclear whether thorn/thornbush wounds the drunkard (so a proverb can be harmful to fools) or is wielded as a weapon by him (so a proverb can harm someone else when offered by fools).
Words translated "archers," "wounding," and "ones passing by" uncertain. Probably something like "An archer who wounds everyone, so he who hires a fool and hires passers-by [is like him]."
Gets excited/angry (which could let to getting involved). Slight change of word (switch around last two consonants) also yields "meddling."
Sense is probably that impassioned/smooth speech to hide an evil heart is like a bath of silver on a clay pot (to hide its cheap/real nature).
Some follow LXX with "smooth." "Fervent lips" on the other hand probably means impassioned speech.
